properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow at time heavy, this afternoon into tonight. Snow is forecast to begin this afternoon. The snow will continue for several hours but may become mix with rain at times near Lake Ontario later today. Then tonight, as temperatures rise, the snow is forecast to transition to rain. A brief period of freezing rain may occur before temperatures rise above zero. By early Monday morning, the rain will transition to snow once again as temperatures fall. Snowfall accumulations in the 5 to 10 cm range are likely, with the heaviest amounts expected inland from Lake Ontario. Travel is expected to be impacted. Motorists should be prepared for winter weather driving conditions. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall expected Sunday into Monday morning. Snow is expected to begin Sunday afternoon. Snowfall amounts of 5 to 10 cm are possible before transitioning to rain Sunday night. Brief freezing rain will be possible Sunday evening. Travel is expected to be impacted due to moderate to heavy snow. Motorists should be prepared for winter weather driving conditions. This is a result of a Colorado Low that will track from Ohio towards the St. Lawrence River Sunday into Monday. There is still some uncertainty in model guidance as to the exact track of the low and the axis of heaviest snow. We will continue to monitor the situation and update Special Weather Statements as new data becomes available. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard conditions are forecast to develop in Clyde River this morning. A low pressure system intensifying over the Davis Strait is bringing snow to the region along with increasing northwesterly winds. Winds gusting at times to 80 km/h are expected to develop this morning resulting in blizzard conditions. Blizzard conditions will persist throughout the afternoon and tonight before improving Monday morning as snow tapers off and winds diminish. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow, rain, and strong winds expected. Total snowfall: 10 to 15 cm. Total rainfall: 25 to 50 mm, with the greatest amounts expected from Red Bay to L'Anse-au-Clair. Maximum wind gusts: southerly 80 km/h on Tuesday becoming northwesterly up to 100 km/h Tuesday night. Locations: southeastern Labrador. Remarks: Snow, at times heavy, is expected to develop Monday evening before changing to rain, at times heavy, overnight Monday night. The rain will be accompanied by strong southerly winds on Tuesday. Precipitation will change back to snow Tuesday evening and will likely combine with strong northwesterly winds to produce a period of blowing snow Tuesday night. Conditions will improve Wednesday morning as the snow and winds taper off. Warnings may be issued in subsequent forecasts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant rain and wind is expected. Locations: Newfoundland. Total rainfall: 30 to 50 mm, with highest amounts in the west and south. Locally higher amounts possible. Maximum wind gusts: 80 to 100 km/h. Stronger coastal gusts possible. Time span: Monday night through Tuesday night. Remarks: Strong southeasterly winds and rain will spread from west to east across the Island Monday night into Tuesday. Rainfall and wind warnings will likely be issued with subsequent forecasts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall and strong winds are expected. Total snowfall: 40 cm or more. Maximum wind gusts: 100 km/h or more. Locations: Upper Lake Melville, Eagle River, and along the coast from Cartwright and vicinity to Postville - Makkovik. Time span: Monday night until Wednesday morning. Remarks: Snow is expected to begin Monday night and become heavy, at times, by Tuesday morning. Strong northerly winds in conjunction with the fresh snowfall will result in poor visibility in blowing snow. Conditions will improve on Wednesday. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Winter storm watches are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall and wind expected beginning Monday night. Total snowfall: 15 to 25 cm. Maximum wind gusts: 80 km/h or higher. Locations: central and northern Labrador. Conditions are expected to improve by Wednesday morning. Watches and warnings may be issued in subsequent forecasts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Special Air Quality Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Stagnant winter weather conditions are creating elevated pollution levels. Higher pollution levels are expected to persist through Monday. The Ministry of Environment and ClimateChange Strategy in collaboration with Northern Health has issued an Air Quality Advisory for Valemount due to high concentrations of fine particulate matter (PM2.5). This advisory remains in effect until further notice. Exposure is particularly a concern for individuals with respiratory infections such as COVID-19, pregnant women, infants, the elderly and those who have diabetes, and lung or heart disease. Persons with chronic underlying medical conditions or acute infections should postpone or reduce strenuous exercise until the advisory is lifted. Anyone experiencing symptoms such as continuing eye or throat irritation, chest discomfort, shortness of breath, cough or wheezing, should follow the advice of their health care provider. Staying indoors helps to reduce fine particulate exposure. Restrictions on open burning are now in effect for all areas within Robson Valley Timber Supply Area until November 23, 2020 at 9:00 AM local time. Real-time air quality observations and information regarding the health effects of air pollution can be found at www.bcairquality.ca Mandatory Emission Reduction Actions: As pollution is occurring or is likely to occur from open burning, pursuant to Section 30 (1) and (2) of the Open Burning Smoke Control Regulation, the Director has prohibited open burning in the Robson Valley Timber Supply Area until November 23, 2020 at 9:00 AM local time. No vegetative debris may be ignited or added to ignited piles. Contravention of these provisions may be subject to a fine under the Regulation. Voluntary Emission Reduction Actions: Where woodstoves or fireplaces are the sole source of residential heat, burn dry woodand ensure an adequate supply of combustion air. Reduce the use and idling of vehicles. ### For more information on current air quality, visit www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/environment/air-land-water/air. Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
